const pageContent = "<div id=\"T4281391803\" page-url=\"menu_web\" class=\"page pinned pinned-top fixed\"><a id=\"menu_web\"></a><div class=\"page-layout\"><div class=\"page-content\"><bodycopy style=\"--fit-height: 10px; --resize-parent-width: 100%;\"><header class=\"header-web\" role=\"banner\">\n  <br>\n  <div class=\"header-web__inner\">\n    <a class=\"header-web__brand\" href=\"#\" rel=\"home-page\">THERE &amp; BACK AGAIN</a>\n\n    <nav aria-label=\"Primary\" class=\"header-web__nav\">\n      <a class=\"header-web__link\" href=\"/chronicles/\" rel=\"history\">CHRONICLES</a>\n      <a class=\"header-web__link\" href=\"/by-region/\" rel=\"history\">BY REGION</a>\n      <a class=\"header-web__link\" href=\"/about-the-traveller/\" rel=\"history\">THE TRAVELLER</a>\n    </nav>\n  </div>\n  <br>\n</header>\n\n<hr class=\"header-rule\"></bodycopy></div></div></div><div style=\"margin-top: 0px; margin-bottom: 0px;\" class=\"pages\"><div id=\"G3465900383\" page-url=\"1-day-in-tarragona-sitges\" class=\"page\"><a id=\"1-day-in-tarragona-sitges\"></a><div class=\"page-layout\"><div class=\"page-content\"><bodycopy style=\"--fit-height: 10px; --resize-parent-width: 100%;\"><!--  POST HERO  -->\n<section class=\"post-hero\">\n  <div class=\"post-route-strip\">\n    <span>Europe</span>&nbsp;· Spain · Catalonia ·&nbsp;<span>Summer 2024</span>\n  </div>\n\n  <h1 class=\"post-hero-title\"><em>1 Day in Tarragona &amp; Sitges:</em> Roman Stone and Seaside Light</h1>\n  <p class=\"post-hero-sub\">One day south from Barcelona — a Roman amphitheatre that opens straight onto the Mediterranean at Tarragona, then the white seaside ease of Sitges. The empire and the holiday on the same coast.</p>\n  <div class=\"post-stats\">\n    <div class=\"stat\"><span class=\"stat-num\">1</span><span class=\"stat-label\">Day</span></div>\n    <div class=\"stat\"><span class=\"stat-num\">2nd C</span><span class=\"stat-label\">Amphitheatre</span></div>\n    <div class=\"stat\"><span class=\"stat-num\">17</span><span class=\"stat-label\">Sitges Beaches</span></div>\n    <div class=\"stat\"><span class=\"stat-num\">~A$157</span><span class=\"stat-label\">Guided Tour</span></div>\n  </div>\n</section>\n\n<!--  OPENING: THE ARRIVAL  -->\n<section class=\"opening-prose\">\n  <div class=\"narrative\">\n    <div class=\"prose\">\n      <p class=\"drop-cap\">The same sea that laps the foot of Barcelona runs south past two very different ideas of what to do with a coastline. An hour down it sits <strong>Tarragona</strong>, which two thousand years ago was <em>Tárraco</em> — the first capital Rome built in Iberia, the city where Augustus wintered while he finished conquering the peninsula, and which still wears its empire in the open: a forum, a circus, a ring of Cyclopean walls, and an amphitheatre cut into the hillside so that the gladiators fought with the Mediterranean filling the gap behind the highest tier of seats. Half an hour back toward Barcelona sits <strong>Sitges</strong>, which has no empire and wants none — a white town of narrow lanes and seventeen beaches, where the only thing built on the rock above the water is a church, and the day's serious business is the light on the sea.</p>\n      <p>This is the day that holds them both: the empire in the morning and the holiday in the afternoon, two answers to the same coast separated by an hour of train and seventeen centuries of intent. Tarragona is what a civilisation does to a shoreline when it means to rule the world from it. Sitges is what people do to a shoreline when the ruling is over and they would simply like to swim. The traveller takes the empire first, while the legs are fresh and the morning light is on the old stone, and saves the easy white town for the long golden end of the day.</p>\n      <p>Both face the same water. Only the ambition differs.</p>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n</section>\n\n<!--  CHAPTER I  -->\n<section class=\"chapter-break\">\n  <div class=\"narrative\">\n    <div class=\"chapter-number\">Chapter I</div>\n    <h2 class=\"chapter-name\"><em>The</em> Empire on the Sea</h2>\n    <p class=\"chapter-epithet\">Tarragona — Roman Tárraco, the amphitheatre on the Mediterranean</p>\n\n    <div class=\"prose\">\n      <p>Tarragona does not present its Roman past behind glass; it lets the traveller walk straight into it. The <strong>amphitheatre</strong> is the image the day is built around — an oval of weathered stone benches dug into the green slope above the harbour, open at one end so that the sea itself becomes the backdrop to the arena, the place where, in the second century, the city watched men kill each other for sport with the Mediterranean glittering behind them. In the year 259 the bishop Fructuosus and two of his deacons were burned alive on this sand under the emperor Valerian; the Visigoths later raised a basilica in the middle of the arena to mark the spot, and the medieval town a small Romanesque church on top of that, so that the oval now holds, stacked in one place, the pagan games, the Christian martyrdom, and the faith that outlasted both. Few ruins anywhere fold so much time into one view.</p>\n      <p>The rest of <em>Tárraco</em> is scattered through the modern city like bones under skin. The <strong>Roman circus</strong>, where chariots once ran, survives in vaulted underground galleries that emerge beside the towering <strong>Praetorium</strong>; the <strong>provincial forum</strong> stands in broken columns among the apartment blocks; and the oldest <strong>city walls</strong>, three kilometres of them, rise on a base of megalithic stones so large the Romans themselves credited them to giants, walkable now along the leafy <strong>Passeig Arqueològic</strong>. Four kilometres out of town the <strong>Pont del Diable</strong> — the Ferreres Aqueduct, the “Devil's Bridge” — strides across a wooded valley on two tiers of perfect arches, as casually monumental as everything Rome built to move water. And at the heart of it all the medieval <strong>cathedral</strong> sits squarely on the foundations of the Temple of Augustus, the Christian church planted, as everywhere in this city, on the exact stone of the empire it replaced.</p>\n      <p>When the old stone is done, the city offers its other face: the <strong>Balcó del Mediterrani</strong>, the iron-railed terrace at the end of the Rambla Nova where Tarragona simply stops and the sea begins, and where the local custom is to <em>tocar ferro</em> — touch the iron railing for luck — before turning back into a town that has been doing exactly this, looking out at this water, for longer than almost anywhere in Spain.</p>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n\n  <aside class=\"pull\">\n    <p>An amphitheatre open at one end, so the gladiators fought with the Mediterranean filling the gap behind the highest seats.</p>\n  </aside>\n</section>\n\n<!--  CHAPTER II  -->\n<section class=\"chapter-break\">\n  <div class=\"narrative\">\n    <div class=\"chapter-number\">Chapter II</div>\n    <h2 class=\"chapter-name\"><em>The</em> Holiday on the Sea</h2>\n    <p class=\"chapter-epithet\">Sitges — the white town, the church on the rock, and the long afternoon light</p>\n\n    <div class=\"prose\">\n      <p>The train north drops the empire behind and arrives, half an hour later, somewhere with no interest in ruling anything. <strong>Sitges</strong> is a low, white, sea-facing town of narrow lanes and bougainvillea and seventeen separate beaches, and its single great monument is the one thing worth monumentalising on a coast like this: the <strong>Església de Sant Bartomeu i Santa Tecla</strong>, a honey-and-ochre church standing alone on a rocky point above the water, dividing the long town beach from the old fishermen's cove, photographed from below until it has become the face of the whole Catalan coast. There are no gladiators here and never were. There is the promenade, the <strong>Passeig Marítim</strong>, running the length of the sand; there is the warm shallow Mediterranean; and there is the particular ease of a town that decided, a long time ago, that the point of the sea is pleasure.</p>\n      <p>It was artists who made that case first. At the turn of the twentieth century the painter Santiago Rusiñol turned Sitges into the headquarters of Catalan <strong>Modernisme</strong>, filling his seafront house — <strong>Cau Ferrat</strong>, now a museum, hung with his collection and two paintings by El Greco — with the bohemian movement that would soon give Barcelona its Gaudí and its dreamlike facades. That inheritance never left: Sitges remains a town of festivals and openness, famous across Europe for its Carnival, for the October film festival that fills it with the fantastic and the macabre, and for being, for decades, one of the most relaxed and welcoming places on the Mediterranean. The traveller does not come here to learn. The traveller comes here to walk the white lanes down to the church on the rock, sit with the light going gold over the water, and let the day soften before the train back to the city.</p>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n</section>\n\n<!--  CHAPTER III  -->\n<section class=\"chapter-break\">\n  <div class=\"narrative\">\n    <div class=\"chapter-number\">Chapter III</div>\n    <h2 class=\"chapter-name\"><em>The</em> Day, Solved</h2>\n    <p class=\"chapter-epithet\">Getting the empire and the holiday into one day, in the right order</p>\n\n    <div class=\"prose\">\n      <p>The geography does the work, and it runs in a tidy line: Barcelona, then Sitges, then Tarragona, all strung along the southern coast on the same rail. The order that wins the day is to <strong>push through to Tarragona first</strong>, while the legs are fresh and the morning light is on the Roman stone, then <strong>come back to Sitges</strong> for the soft end of the afternoon, when a white seaside town is at its best and the only remaining task is to find the right spot to watch the sea. Do it the other way and the day arrives at the ruins tired and leaves the beach in the heat of noon — both halves diminished.</p>\n      <p>The trip solved it the simple way, with a <strong>guided day tour</strong> from Barcelona (around <strong>A$157</strong>) that bundled the driving, the order and the Roman context into one early start (around 08:15) and a late-afternoon return. The independent version is genuinely easy for the confident: regional <strong>Rodalies trains</strong> reach Tarragona in a little over an hour and Sitges in about thirty-five minutes, and the two towns are themselves only a short hop apart on the coastal line. However the day is done, it ends back in Barcelona, and on this trip it ended in the best small way the city offers: standing up at <strong>Quimet &amp; Quimet</strong> in Poble Sec, the tiny four-generation bottle-lined bar where dinner is a sequence of <em>montaditos</em> built to order and a glass of something poured from one of a hundred bottles — the empire and the beach both behind, the city close and loud again.</p>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n</section>\n\n<div class=\"ornament\">· · · ✦ · · ·</div>\n\n<div class=\"beat\">The Roman sea and the swimming sea were the same sea all along.</div>\n\n<!--  PRACTICAL: GETTING THERE  -->\n<section class=\"practical\">\n  <div class=\"prac-header\">\n    <div class=\"prac-city\">Getting There &amp; Around</div>\n    <div class=\"prac-dates\">From Barcelona · Summer 2024</div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"prac-section\">\n    <div class=\"prac-label\">From Barcelona</div>\n    <div class=\"prac-item\">Both towns sit south on the same coastal rail. Regional <strong>Rodalies/Media Distancia trains</strong> reach central <strong>Tarragona</strong> in a little over an hour; the <strong>R2 Sud</strong> line reaches <strong>Sitges</strong> in about 35 minutes from Barcelona Sants or Passeig de Gràcia.</div>\n    <div class=\"prac-item\">Sitges and Tarragona are a short hop apart on the coastal line (roughly 30–40 minutes) — what makes the pairing a clean single day.</div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"prac-section\">\n    <div class=\"prac-label\">The Easy Option</div>\n    <div class=\"prac-item\">The trip took a <strong>guided day tour</strong> from Barcelona (around <strong>A$157</strong>), bundling transport, the order and the Roman context. Departs early (~08:15), back by late afternoon.</div>\n  </div>\n</section>\n\n<!--  PRACTICAL: ROMAN TARRAGONA  -->\n<section class=\"practical\">\n  <div class=\"prac-header\">\n    <div class=\"prac-city\">Roman Tarragona — Sites &amp; Tickets</div>\n    <div class=\"prac-dates\">Costs in AUD (€ noted)</div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"prac-section\">\n    <div class=\"prac-label\">The Empire</div>\n    <div class=\"prac-item\"><strong>Amfiteatre Romà</strong> (the amphitheatre on the sea) — a few euros; the centrepiece, and the one not to skip.</div>\n    <div class=\"prac-item\"><strong>Combined Tárraco ticket</strong> — covers the amphitheatre, the <strong>Circ Romà &amp; Praetorium</strong>, the <strong>forum</strong> and the <strong>Passeig Arqueològic</strong> walls; around <strong>A$25 (€15)</strong> and far better value than single entries.</div>\n    <div class=\"prac-item\"><strong>Pont del Diable</strong> (Ferreres Aqueduct) — free; 4 km out of town, reachable by city bus.</div>\n    <div class=\"prac-item\"><strong>Tarragona Cathedral</strong> — a few euros, built over the Temple of Augustus. The <strong>Balcó del Mediterrani</strong> is free.</div>\n  </div>\n</section>\n\n<!--  PRACTICAL: SITGES  -->\n<section class=\"practical\">\n  <div class=\"prac-header\">\n    <div class=\"prac-city\">Sitges — On the Day</div>\n    <div class=\"prac-dates\">White town, church, sea</div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"prac-section\">\n    <div class=\"prac-label\">Don't Miss</div>\n    <div class=\"prac-item\"><strong>The church on the rock</strong> — Sant Bartomeu i Santa Tecla, above the water between two beaches, is the photograph and the orientation point.</div>\n    <div class=\"prac-item\"><strong>Cau Ferrat &amp; Maricel museums</strong> — a few euros each, for the Modernisme story and a sea view; Cau Ferrat holds two El Grecos.</div>\n    <div class=\"prac-item\"><strong>The Passeig Marítim</strong> — walk it, swim, and find a spot for the late light. Eat local: <em>xató</em> salad and the town's <em>malvasia</em> wine.</div>\n  </div>\n</section>\n\n<!--  PRACTICAL: TIPS & WATCH-OUTS  -->\n<section class=\"practical\">\n  <div class=\"prac-header\">\n    <div class=\"prac-city\">Tips &amp; Watch-outs</div>\n    <div class=\"prac-dates\">The rules that save the day</div>\n  </div>\n\n  <div class=\"prac-section\">\n    <div class=\"prac-label\">Get It Right</div>\n    <div class=\"tip-row\"><strong>Tarragona first, Sitges second.</strong> Ruins in the fresh morning, beach town in the golden afternoon.</div>\n    <div class=\"tip-row\"><strong>Buy the combined Tárraco ticket.</strong> Amphitheatre, circus, forum and walls for far less than paying gate by gate.</div>\n    <div class=\"tip-row\"><strong>Wear real shoes for Tarragona.</strong> The Roman sites are stone, slope and uneven ground — not a beach-sandal morning.</div>\n    <div class=\"tip-row\"><strong>Sitges is a swim town.</strong> The church and the lanes take an hour; the sea takes as long as you let it.</div>\n    <div class=\"tip-row\"><strong>Take the tour if you want the Roman context.</strong> Tárraco rewards a guide — without one, much of it reads as handsome rubble.</div>\n  </div>\n</section>\n\n<!--  VIATOR TOURS  -->\n<div class=\"tours\">\n  <div class=\"tours-label\">Guided Experiences — Tarragona &amp; Sitges</div>\n  <div class=\"tours-grid\">\n    <a class=\"tour-card\" href=\"https://www.viator.com/tours/Barcelona/Tarragona-and-Sitges-Small-Group-Day-Trip-from-Barcelona/d562-3142TARRA?pid=P00295455&amp;mcid=42383&amp;medium=link\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">\n      <div class=\"tour-type\">Small Group</div>\n      <div class=\"tour-name\">Tarragona &amp; Sitges Small-Group Day Trip</div>\n      <div class=\"tour-meta\">Roman Tarragona in the morning, the white town of Sitges in the afternoon — the order and the context handled.</div>\n      <div class=\"tour-footer\">\n        <span class=\"tour-price\">Day trip from Barcelona</span>\n        <span class=\"tour-link-label\">View on Viator →</span>\n      </div>\n    </a>\n    <a class=\"tour-card\" href=\"https://www.viator.com/tours/Barcelona/Tarragona-and-Sitges-tour/d562-9866P25?pid=P00295455&amp;mcid=42383&amp;medium=link\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">\n      <div class=\"tour-type\">Hotel Pickup</div>\n      <div class=\"tour-name\">Tarragona &amp; Sitges — Small Group with Hotel Transfer</div>\n      <div class=\"tour-meta\">The same two-town day with hotel pickup included — the no-logistics version of the trip's own day.</div>\n      <div class=\"tour-footer\">\n        <span class=\"tour-price\">Full-day from Barcelona</span>\n        <span class=\"tour-link-label\">View on Viator →</span>\n      </div>\n    </a>\n    <a class=\"tour-card\" href=\"https://www.viator.com/tours/Barcelona/Tarragona-and-Sitges-Private-Day-Trip-from-Barcelona/d562-3142TARRA_P?pid=P00295455&amp;mcid=42383&amp;medium=link\" rel=\"noopener\" target=\"_blank\">\n      <div class=\"tour-type\">Private</div>\n      <div class=\"tour-name\">Tarragona &amp; Sitges Private Day Trip</div>\n      <div class=\"tour-meta\">The two coasts at your own pace, private guide and vehicle — more time at the ruins or more time by the sea, your call.</div>\n      <div class=\"tour-footer\">\n        <span class=\"tour-price\">Private · from Barcelona</span>\n        <span class=\"tour-link-label\">View on Viator →</span>\n      </div>\n    </a>\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n<!--  ITINERARY  -->\n<section class=\"itin-block\">\n  <div class=\"itin-inner\">\n    <div class=\"itin-block-title\">One Day from Barcelona at a Glance</div>\n\n    <p class=\"itin-meta\">Shape: <strong>a single long day south, the empire and the holiday</strong>.</p>\n    <p class=\"itin-meta\">Booked as: <strong>guided tour, ~A$157 per person</strong>.</p>\n\n    <div class=\"itin-section-head\">Tarragona &amp; Sitges — day trip</div>\n    <div class=\"itin-days\">\n      <div class=\"itin-day-row\"><span class=\"itin-day-num\">~08:15</span>Depart Barcelona, south along the coast.</div>\n      <div class=\"itin-day-row\"><span class=\"itin-day-num\">Morning</span><strong>Roman Tarragona</strong>: the amphitheatre on the sea, the circus and Praetorium, the megalithic walls, the cathedral on the Temple of Augustus, the Balcó del Mediterrani.</div>\n      <div class=\"itin-day-row\"><span class=\"itin-day-num\">Midday</span>North to <strong>Sitges</strong>.</div>\n      <div class=\"itin-day-row\"><span class=\"itin-day-num\">PM</span>The <strong>church on the rock</strong>, the white lanes, the <strong>Passeig Marítim</strong>, a swim and the long light over the water.</div>\n      <div class=\"itin-day-row\"><span class=\"itin-day-num\">Eve</span>Back to Barcelona. Dinner standing up at <strong>Quimet &amp; Quimet</strong> in Poble Sec.</div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n</section>\n\n<!--  CLOSING REFLECTION  -->\n<section class=\"post-closing\">\n  <div class=\"narrative\">\n    <div class=\"prose\">\n      <p>The coast runs back toward the city in the late light, the white town behind and the Roman stone behind that, and the day arranges itself into the two ideas it was always about. Tarragona was ambition turned to architecture — a civilisation that looked at this water and decided to govern an empire from beside it, and left an amphitheatre, a circus and three kilometres of giant-built wall to prove the seriousness of the intent. Sitges was the opposite of ambition, and none the worse for it: a town that looked at the same sea and built a single church on a rock and seventeen ways down to the sand, and asked nothing of the visitor but that they enjoy the afternoon.</p>\n      <p>The traveller carries both back to the city, and finds them oddly easy to hold together. The empire and the holiday are not opposites so much as the same coast read at two speeds — the one that conquers and the one that finally, gratefully, stops. Barcelona is close again now, the train filling, a tiny bottle-lined bar in Poble Sec waiting with the night's first <em>montadito</em>. The Roman sea and the swimming sea were the same sea all along.</p>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n</section>\n\n<div class=\"beat\">But the road is ever onward.</div>\n\n<!--  FAQ  -->\n<section class=\"faq-block\">\n  <div class=\"faq-inner\">\n    <div class=\"faq-item\">\n      <div class=\"faq-q\">Is Tarragona worth a day trip from Barcelona?</div>\n      <div class=\"faq-a\">Yes — Tarragona was Roman Tárraco, the first Roman capital in Iberia, and its ruins are a UNESCO World Heritage site: a second-century amphitheatre that opens onto the Mediterranean, a Roman circus, a provincial forum, three kilometres of ancient walls, and an aqueduct outside town. It's a little over an hour from Barcelona by train, and pairs naturally with the seaside town of Sitges on the way back.</div>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"faq-item\">\n      <div class=\"faq-q\">Can you visit Tarragona and Sitges in the same day?</div>\n      <div class=\"faq-a\">Comfortably. Both sit south of Barcelona on the same coastal rail line, with Sitges roughly halfway. The best order is Tarragona first, in the fresh morning light, then Sitges for the afternoon and the late sun over the sea, then back to Barcelona for the evening.</div>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"faq-item\">\n      <div class=\"faq-q\">How do you get from Barcelona to Tarragona and Sitges?</div>\n      <div class=\"faq-a\">Regional Rodalies/Media Distancia trains reach central Tarragona in a little over an hour; the R2 Sud line reaches Sitges in about 35 minutes from Barcelona Sants or Passeig de Gràcia. The two towns are a short hop apart on the coastal line. Many visitors take a guided day tour that handles the transport and the order.</div>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"faq-item\">\n      <div class=\"faq-q\">What is there to see in Roman Tarragona?</div>\n      <div class=\"faq-a\">The amphitheatre on the sea is the centrepiece, with a Visigothic basilica built in the arena where Bishop Fructuosus was martyred in 259. Add the Roman circus and Praetorium tower, the provincial forum, the megalithic city walls along the Passeig Arqueològic, the Ferreres Aqueduct outside town, and the cathedral built over the Temple of Augustus. A combined ticket covers most of it.</div>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"faq-item\">\n      <div class=\"faq-q\">What is Sitges known for?</div>\n      <div class=\"faq-a\">Sitges is a white-walled seaside town with seventeen beaches and an iconic church, Sant Bartomeu i Santa Tecla, on a rock above the water. It was a cradle of Catalan Modernisme — the painter Santiago Rusiñol's house, Cau Ferrat, is now a museum — and is famous for its Carnival, its October fantasy-and-horror film festival, and decades as one of the most relaxed and welcoming towns on the Mediterranean.</div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n</section>\n\n\n\n<!--  FURTHER READING  -->\n<section class=\"next-chronicles\">\n  <div class=\"narrative\">\n    <h2 class=\"chapter-name\" style=\"text-align:center; margin-bottom: 2.5rem;\"><em>Further</em> Reading</h2>\n    <div class=\"posts-grid\">\n      <a class=\"post-card\" href=\"/7-days-in-barcelona-gaud%C3%AD%27s-unfinished-argument/\" rel=\"history\">\n        <div class=\"post-region\">Spain · Catalonia</div>\n        <div class=\"post-title\">Barcelona: Gaudí's Unfinished Argument</div>\n        <div class=\"post-excerpt\">The base city this day departs from — Gaudí, the Gothic Quarter, and a city that never stops building.</div>\n      <div class=\"post-meta\">7 days&nbsp;<span class=\"dot\"></span>&nbsp;City Guide</div>\n      </a>\n      <a class=\"post-card\" href=\"/1-day-in-figueres-girona/\" rel=\"history\">\n        <div class=\"post-region\">Spain · Catalonia</div>\n        <div class=\"post-title\">Figueres &amp; Girona: A Day Inside Dalí's Mind</div>\n        <div class=\"post-excerpt\">The other long day trip from Barcelona — the surrealist's museum-tomb, and a stacked medieval city on a painted river.</div>\n      <div class=\"post-meta\">1 day&nbsp;<span class=\"dot\"></span>&nbsp;Day Trip</div>\n      </a>\n      <a class=\"post-card\" href=\"/4-weeks-portugal-to-spain-by-rail-road/\" rel=\"history\">\n        <div class=\"post-region\">Iberia · Circuit</div>\n        <div class=\"post-title\">Portugal to Spain by Rail and Road</div>\n        <div class=\"post-excerpt\">The full thirty-day circuit — Porto to Barcelona, almost entirely overland, with the costs laid bare.</div>\n      <div class=\"post-meta\">4 weeks&nbsp;<span class=\"dot\"></span>&nbsp;Chronicle</div>\n      </a>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n</section></bodycopy></div></div></div></div>";
